Importing the the trainining and the testing data seperatly for clarity. When importing the data since there was an error in the formating of the CSV files meaning that an extra columns of data was created for the two features relating to state names, a work-around was implemented by importing the data without the feature names attached, then removing the excess columns (i.e columns indices 26,35) and then afterwards reapplying the orginal column head titles.

Additionally, NA values for the columns 'Disruption' were removed. The NA values for 'Disruption' were removed as it was the column which we were trying to predict and thus it would have been mis-representitive if we imputted data for the truth column.

filepaths = [
    '/cs/datasets/ID5059/Coursework1/3_large/Combined_Flights_large_train_2018.csv',
    '/cs/datasets/ID5059/Coursework1/3_large/Combined_Flights_large_train_2019.csv',

    '/cs/datasets/ID5059/Coursework1/3_large/Combined_Flights_large_train_2022.csv'
]

# Specify the column indices to drop
columns_to_drop_indices = [26, 35]

# Storing Column Names
first_file = filepaths[0]
df_names = pd.read_csv(first_file, nrows=0)
column_names = df_names.columns.tolist()

# Initialize an empty list to store DataFrames
dfs = []

# Iterate through each file path in the list
for filepath in filepaths:
    
    # Read the CSV file into a DataFrame, skipping the first row
    df = pd.read_csv(filepath, skiprows=1, header=None)

    # Convert indices to column names for columns to drop
    columns_to_drop = df.columns[columns_to_drop_indices]

    # Drop the specified columns and reassign to df
    df = df.drop(columns=columns_to_drop, axis=1)
    
    # Append the processed DataFrame to the list
    dfs.append(df)
    
    # Concatenate all DataFrames in the list into one DataFrame
    combined_df = pd.concat(dfs, ignore_index=True)

# Assigning Column Names
combined_df.columns = column_names

# Dropping na rows since Disruption is truth column so should not be imputed
combined_df = combined_df.dropna(subset=['Disruption'])

Splitting data into test and valadation set

The test data was split into an 80/20 split so that 20% of the data could be used as a validation set. Ideally we would have preffered to use K-fold cross validation instead but due to computational limitations this was not possible and hence the choice of using a valdation set was selected instead.

The output above highlights an issue that many of the attributes are stored as type 'int64' when they are infact categorical, the impact of this is seen when the histograms are plotted below as many of the features such as 'year' have been interpreted as a continuous variables when in fact they should be considered categorical since there are only 5 of them present in our data. This results in a historgram only showing values at the values which the categories represent (spikes at relevent categories).

Another observation can be made from the final output of the number of NA values for each column that after having dropped the NA values for 'Disruption' ,with the reason mentioned before,the only column that contains missing values is the Tail_Number and CRSElapsedTime. This is very useful for the data exploration section as it means we have an almost complete dataset without having to do any imputation of data. Since Tail_Number was not considered a useful feature to include in the model its values were not imputed and it was discarded.

Now that we can see which features have been included in the dataset we can begin by identifying which features might be of interest and further analysis, these features and their justifications have been listed below.

  • FlightDate : The date a flight departs could have an impact on wether it is going to be delayed as some days may a higher rate of disruption due to an increased overal rate of travel (e.g public holidays / summer season) another reason why it may be influencal is due to environmental issues, for example there may be a higher rate of disruption during certain time periods like during winter as the weather could affect how many flights are able to depart on time.

  • Airline: The disruption rate may vary by airline since each airline operates as independent companies and hence may have independent disruptions rate. This could be for example that some airlines could have a higher rate of disruption due as they are operating a much larger volume of shorter flight and delays are more likely to occour with several back to back short flights compred to a single long haul flight.

  • Origin: The airport from which a plane departs could have an impact on if it is delayed since each aiport would have varying levels of traffic and so possibly airports that have higher levels of traffic may have a higher rate of disruption.

  • Dest: Similarly to Origin destination airports that have a higher level of traffic may also cause a higher rate of disruption since if an airport is extremely busy, aircrafts are usually given a very specific time slot for when they can land, if this small window is missed then sometimes planes are forced to wait for a next available slot, this waiting time could therefore cause delays.

  • 'CRSDepTime','CRSArrTime': Represents the Computer Reservation System Departure Time, this is essentially when the flight is meant to depart from its origin airport. This is not when the flight actually departs but instead an indication of when it is scheduled to, this could have an impact since flight travelling during parts of the day may have a different rate of disruption. An example could be that airlines that operate short haul flights, usually have many sucessive flights one after another, this would mean that if a delay were to occour on an earlier flight this could have a knock on impact on flights later on in the day.

  • 'CRSElapsedTime': The predicted flight time gives an indication of how long the flight is meant to take, and hence how far it is predicted to travel, the connection to disruption as mentioned before is that shorter flights may be prone to a higher rate of disruption due to the fact that they usually occour back to back one after another so flights which are going further occour less often and possibly are less disrupted.

  • 'Distance': This feature links to discussions about CRSElapsedTime and investigations will be done below to see if there is a interaction between these two features

  • 'Year','Quarter','Month','DayofMonth','DayOfWeek': These catagorical features have also been investigated with the same reasoning as before that certain categories may have different rate of disruption.

Additionally to all of the features described above some others were also included in the exploration stage just for completness and to give better insight in case any features gave useful information to the model.

Insights from the histograms above:

  • As suspected the histogram has interpreted some of the categorical columns as numeric and hence has spikes where the categories are, this does give an insight into the frequency of flights for each catagory for example that Saturday (day 6) seems to have less flights than other days.
  • There appears to be an imbalence in the frequency of flights throughout the years and this is investigated further below
  • The scales of the numeric attributes vary such as time from 0-2400 to distance which goes from 0-6000. This will mean that in the pre-processing stage a standardiser will need to be implemented to correct for this.
  • Some histograms are tail heavy (both right and left skewed), this could could cause issues for the Machine learning models as it may be harder for them to detect patterns, this will be correct again by standerdising the data to produce more "bell-shaped" distributions.

The next step of the exploration will be to plot some of the more interesting fetures in more depth. The figure below shows some of thes selected categorical features, they have been plotted to show to show the proportion of them which have disrupted flights vs not disrupted. This has been done so that if there is a trend of the proportion of flights from a certain category then this will be seen more clearly as the bars will deviate more from the same height. This was done as there was an imbalence in the frequency of many categories so when the frequency was plotted instead it made it harder to determine where imbalences of proportions were, which is the more imformative metric. This being said this did have the impact that were the frequency of a category was very low the proportion metric became very volatile since each entry for this category had a much larger weighting, this will be seen below.

In[7]:
# List of columns to create bar charts for
columns_to_plot = ['Marketing_Airline_Network', 'OriginState', 'DestState', 'DepTimeBlk', 'ArrTimeBlk', 'Airline', 'DistanceGroup', 'Year', 'Quarter', 'DayofMonth','DayOfWeek']

# Adjust the figure size for a more condensed plot and set the legend to display only once
figsize = (10, 4)  # Adjust figure size to make plots more condensed

for column in columns_to_plot:
    # Calculate the count of disrupted vs. not disrupted flights for each category in the column
    disrupted_counts = df.groupby([column, 'Disruption']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)
    
    # Calculate the proportion of disrupted flights for each category
    disrupted_proportions = disrupted_counts.div(disrupted_counts.sum(axis=1), axis=0)
    
    # Plot the proportions
    ax = disrupted_proportions.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=figsize, colormap='viridis', legend=False)
    plt.title(f'Proportion of Flights Disrupted by {column}')
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel('Proportion of Flights')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, fontsize=9)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Show the legend separately
handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 1))  # An arbitrary figure size to fit the legend
plt.legend(handles, ['Not Disrupted', 'Disrupted'], title='Status', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.axis('off')  # Hide axes

plt.show()

Discussion about the plots above:

  • 'Airline','OriginState' and 'DestState': all of these features seemed to have some imbalence in their categories meaning that they could be useful columns to include. A note here is that for the 'OriginState' graph there is a dip for the DE state this is because as mentioned above there were very few flights coming this state meaning its disribution was ill-representive. This should not be reason for consern however as when the information is passed into the model it will only account for a very few number of entries and hence will not cause any major impact for other predictions.

  • 'Year','Quarter','DayofMonth','DayOfWeek': All seemed to have relatively balanced catategories of proportions of flights being disrupted and hence would not be very useful when trying to predict for new data.

  • 'DepTimeBlk','ArrTimeBlk': Both displayed a very interesting smooth trend of proportion of flights being cancelled and so very much seemed to have a influence in disruption. The only reason they were not included in the model is because using the other numeric columns 'CRSDepTime','CRSArrTime' give essentially the same information as these categorical features, this is shown in the figures below where the continuous numerical columns were discretised into bins and again showed the trends seen in these categorical features.

The thing to note with the analysis is that it would only detect linear relationships between the target varible so further analysis must be done to detect non-linear relationships too.

From the above we can see that 'CRSDepTime','CRSArrTime' seem to have a correlation to the disruption and so they were all included in the model. More analysis of other features sich as 'CRSElapsedTime' will be done to see if it is worth being put into the model. With these features we have conducted a Spearman which is a non-parametric test (does not rely on assumptions about distribution of data) to identify if there is a monotonic relationship (linear/non-linear) between the features and 'Disruption'.

In[10]:
# Droping small number of NA value CRSElapsedTime so that Spearman's test works
df = df.dropna(subset=['CRSElapsedTime'])
numeric_columns = ['CRSDepTime','CRSArrTime','CRSElapsedTime','Distance']

# Iterate over numeric columns
for col in numeric_columns:
    # Skip the 'Disruption' column itself
    if col == 'Disruption':
        continue
    
    # Perform Spearman's rank correlation test
    corr, p_value = spearmanr(df[col], df['Disruption'])
    
    # Print the results
    print(f"{col}: Spearman's correlation coefficient = {corr:.3f}, P-value = {p_value:.3f}")

CRSDepTime: Spearman's correlation coefficient = 0.125, P-value = 0.000
CRSArrTime: Spearman's correlation coefficient = 0.114, P-value = 0.000
CRSElapsedTime: Spearman's correlation coefficient = 0.021, P-value = 0.000
Distance: Spearman's correlation coefficient = 0.020, P-value = 0.000

From the results of this test we can see that all the features appear as significant and hence a montonic relationship is present. However not that 'CRSElapsedTime' and 'Distance' seem to have a weak correlation but we still included in the model since they were still considered significant by the test.

The next step is to investigate the trend that we determined of the variation of the frequency of flight during the years the data was recorded. This has been done by grouping the data by the number of disrupted flights by month across the entire span of time provided too see if there is a trend present.

In[11]:
# Splitting Flight Date up by month to show how frequency of flights vary
df['FlightDate'] = pd.to_datetime(df['FlightDate'])
df['YearMonth'] = df['FlightDate'].dt.to_period('M')
monthly_disruptions = df[df['Disruption'] == True].groupby('YearMonth').size()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
monthly_disruptions.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Monthly Disruptions')
plt.xlabel('Year-Month')
plt.ylabel('Number of Disruptions')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate the x-axis labels for better readability
plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to make room for the rotated x-axis labels
plt.show()

From the graph above we can see there is a signifcant drop in the frequency in flights between April of 2020 and April of 2021. Of course we are aware of external factors, such as Covid 19 pandemic had a huge impact on the airline industry and this is the trend we are witnessing here. To counteract this we will feature engineer a new column as a binary indicator as to if a flight occoured between this period of not, this will hopefully help the model account for this dip in the frequency of data during this period.

The next step is to analyse the trend between 'CRSElapsedTime' and 'Disruption' in greater depth and see if it is worth including it in the model. This has been done below by creating a graph showing one the frequency of flights in discretised bins for this feature as well as the proportion of these flights that were disrupted.

#function to plot the disruption rate for a given feature with vertical bars
def plot_disruption_rate_by_feature_vertical(feature, data, top_n=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    # If top_n is specified, filter the data to include only the top_n categories by frequency
    if top_n:
        top_categories = data[feature].value_counts().nlargest(top_n).index
        filtered_data = data[data[feature].isin(top_categories)]
    else:
        filtered_data = data
    
    # Calculate the disruption rate
    disruption_rate = filtered_data.groupby(feature)['Disruption'].mean().reset_index().sort_values(by='Disruption', ascending=True)
    
    # Create the vertical bar plot
    sns.barplot(x=feature, y='Disruption', data=disruption_rate)
    plt.title(f'Disruption Rate by {feature}')
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel('Disruption Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plotting for each feature with vertical bars

  • CRSArrTime

The last two being the two engineered features. Pandemic being a binary indictor of wether the flight took place during the period Covid 19 affected disruptions significantly. FlightAverage being the average of Distance and CRSElapsedTime once they had been standerdised.

Remarks:

Used the large dataset rather than using the huge one, the reason for this was that the computation necessary for the huge one would have taken too long for it to run in a reasonable ammount of time. In addition to the there was not a major change in the results from the medium to large datasets so it is likely that this would mean that moving to the huge would not have made a significant change to my findings.

The next few cells are the code related to the custom transformers that had to be made to add the new engineered features to the processed data.

The first relates to the binary indicator for the period during Covid 19 for the Pandemic feature.

In[16]:
class PandemicIndicatorTransformer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self):
        # This transformer does not need any initialization parameters
        pass

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        # Nothing to fit, so just return self
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        
        # Create a copy of X to avoid altering the original data
        X_transformed = X.copy()
        
        # Convert FlightDate to datetime format if it's not already
        X_transformed['FlightDate'] = pd.to_datetime(X_transformed['FlightDate'])
        
        # Define the start and end of the pandemic period
        pandemic_start = pd.Timestamp('2020-04-01')
        pandemic_end = pd.Timestamp('2021-04-30')
        
        # Create the 'Pandemic' column based on the condition
        X_transformed['Pandemic'] = ((X_transformed['FlightDate'] >= pandemic_start) & 
                                     (X_transformed['FlightDate'] <= pandemic_end)).astype(int)
        
        # Drop the 'FlightDate' column as it should not be included in the transformed DataFrame
        X_transformed.drop(columns=['FlightDate'], inplace=True)
        
        return X_transformed

The second relates to the added feature combining the data of 'CRSElapsedTime' and 'Distance' into one new engineered feature, being called FlightAverage

In[17]:
class AverageFlightTransformer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self):
        # This transformer does not need any initialization parameters
        pass

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        # Nothing to fit, so just return self
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        # Ensure X is a DataFrame
        if not isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame):
            raise ValueError("Input is not a pandas DataFrame")
        
        # Create a copy of X to avoid altering the original data
        X_transformed = X.copy()

        # Impute missing data in 'CRSElapsedTime' with the median value
        imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='median')
        X_transformed['CRSElapsedTime'] = imputer.fit_transform(X_transformed[['CRSElapsedTime']])

        # Standerdising the two columns before calculating their mean
        mean_ElapsedTime = np.mean(X_transformed['CRSElapsedTime'],axis=0)
        std_ElapsedTime = np.std(X_transformed['CRSElapsedTime'],axis=0)
        
        scaled_data_ElapsedTime = (X_transformed['CRSElapsedTime'] - mean_ElapsedTime) / std_ElapsedTime
        
        mean_Distance = np.mean(X_transformed['Distance'],axis=0)
        std_Distance = np.std(X_transformed['Distance'],axis=0)
        
        scaled_data_Distance = (X_transformed['Distance'] - mean_Distance) / std_Distance
        
        
        # Create the 'FlightAverage' column based on the condition
        X_transformed['FlightAverage'] = (scaled_data_ElapsedTime+scaled_data_Distance)/2
        
        # Drop the 'FlightDate' column as it should not be included in the transformed DataFrame
        X_transformed.drop(columns=['CRSElapsedTime','Distance'], inplace=True)
        
        return X_transformed

This transformer was added so that the if the data being inputed into the model contained missing values for the categorical sections it would need to have been imputed before being processed by the model. The below shows a transformer that would imput the data for this column based on the most frequent value of the column.

In[18]:
class CategoricalImputerMostFrequent(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self):
        # This transformer does not need to be initialized with any parameters.
        pass

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        
        X_transformed = X.copy()
        
        # Check if X is a DataFrame
        if not isinstance(X_transformed, pd.DataFrame):
            raise ValueError("Input is not a pandas DataFrame")
        
        self.most_frequent_ = X_transformed.mode().iloc[0]
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        check_is_fitted(self, 'most_frequent_')
        
        X_transformed = X.copy()
        
        X_filled = X_transformed.fillna(self.most_frequent_)
        return X_filled

This cell below shows all of these pre-processing steps being put into one pipeline called 'full_pipeline' that is able to do 4 things:

  • Imput missing data for both the numeric and categorical columns
  • Add the new custom engineered features to the dataset
  • Standardise the numeric columns to so that they have a more bell shapped distribution
  • It also converts the categories into numeric values based on the target column using target encoding. This final point was elected as when using OneHotEncoding which is the norm for categorical information the processing time far excedded a reasonable ammount of time, so this method was chosen an alternative.

Pipeline

In[19]:
# transformations on numerical columns
num_pipeline = Pipeline([
            ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy="median")),
            ('std_scaler', StandardScaler()),
        ])

# Transformation for Categorical columns
categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', CategoricalImputerMostFrequent()),
    ('target_encoder', TargetEncoder())
])

# Pandemic Transformer
pandemic_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('covid_indicator', PandemicIndicatorTransformer()),
])

# FlightAverage Transformer
average_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('average_length', AverageFlightTransformer()),
])

# Full pipeline containing all the pre-processing steps necessary
full_pipeline = ColumnTransformer([
                ("num", num_pipeline, num_attribs),
                ('average',average_transformer,['CRSElapsedTime','Distance']),
                ("covid", pandemic_transformer, ['FlightDate']),
                ('cat_impute', categorical_transformer , cat_attribs)
         ])

Model Selection

Plotting ROC curve for Decision Tree, Random Forest and SGD Classifier

The ROC curve (Receiver Operating Characteristic curve), has been used to evalutae the performance of the binary classification models across different thresholds.

The ROC curve plots TPR vs FPR:

  • True Positive Rate (TPR), also known as sensitivity or recall, on the y-axis. It is defined as (TP / (TP + FN)), where (TP) is the number of true positives and (FN) is the number of false negatives. The TPR measures the proportion of actual positives correctly identified.

  • False Positive Rate (FPR), on the x-axis. It is calculated as (FP / (FP + TN)), where (FP) is the number of false positives and (TN) is the number of true negatives. The FPR measures the proportion of actual negatives that are incorrectly classified as positives.

The ROC curve demonstrates the trade-off between sensitivity and specificity (1 - FPR) at various thresholds. A perfect classifier's ROC curve would reach the top left corner of the plot, indicating a TPR of 1 and an FPR of 0. As seen from the models below none of the models do an amazing job at reaching this corner however the graph still provided useful insight into which model is working better.

The AUC summarizes the entire ROC curve in a single value, representing the likelihood that a classifier will rank a randomly chosen positive instance higher than a randomly chosen negative one. Values range from 0 to 1, with 0.5 indicating no discriminative ability and 1.0 indicating perfect discrimination.

Having completed this grid search, below I have outlined which combination of parameters ended up being the best combination. As we can see the combination of n_estimators = 30 and max_depth = 15 was selected however both of these lie at end of their respective choice meaning that bettter values for the parameters may lie outside our designated search grid. Ideally we would add more parameters to our grid search to ensure that these parameters are the optimal combination rather than the best that was possible with the given inputs. This was not done however since it would have greatly increased computation gain and after outputting the AUC for each combination there are minimal gains to be made irrelevent of the combination being selected, so the cost vs reward here would not be in favour of adding new grid search parameters.

Note: Ideally we would have also used K-fold Cross Valadation here but again due to computational limitations this was not possible in this senario. The benefits of this method would have been that it would reduce bias of the data which have been caused by this particular split of data, it better generalises the data meaning less chance of overfitting and finally is more robust against imbalances in data which is the case here since the majority of flights are not disrupted.

Result Analysis

Calculating a 95% confidence interval for the test set AUC, as the single AUC value above doesn't give an indication of how much variance there was in this value. This was done by creating a non-parametric bootstrap, using resampling with replacement.

In[27]:
# Function to perform bootstrapping and calculate AUC confidence interval
def bootstrap_auc_ci(y_true, y_scores, n_bootstraps=1000, alpha=0.95):
    rng = np.random.RandomState(seed=42)  # Seed for reproducibility
    bootstrapped_aucs = []
    
    y_true = np.array(y_true)
    y_scores = np.array(y_scores)
    
    for _ in range(n_bootstraps):
        # Randomly generate indices for the bootstrap sample
        indices = rng.randint(0, len(y_true), len(y_true))
        # Use the randomly generated indices to create the bootstrap sample
        y_true_sample = y_true[indices]
        y_scores_sample = y_scores[indices]
        # Calculate the AUC for the bootstrap sample
        if len(np.unique(y_true_sample)) > 1:  # Check if the sample contains more than one class
            auc_score = roc_auc_score(y_true_sample, y_scores_sample)
            bootstrapped_aucs.append(auc_score)
    
    # Calculate the confidence interval bounds
    lower_bound = np.percentile(bootstrapped_aucs, 100 * ((1 - alpha) / 2))
    upper_bound = np.percentile(bootstrapped_aucs, 100 * (alpha + (1 - alpha) / 2))
    
    return lower_bound, upper_bound


# Calculate AUC
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)
print(f"AUC: {auc}")

# Estimate the confidence interval for the AUC
alpha = 0.95  # 95% confidence interval
lower, upper = bootstrap_auc_ci(y_test, y_pred_proba, n_bootstraps=500, alpha=alpha)
print(f"{alpha*100}% Confidence interval for the AUC: [{lower:.3f}, {upper:.3f}]")

AUC: 0.6488709155885555
95.0% Confidence interval for the AUC: [0.647, 0.651]

From this we can see that CRSDepTime is the most important feature, followed up by CRSArrTime and then FlightAverage our engineered feature of the average of distance and time elapsed. Interestingly the importance of the airline was roughly the same as wether the flight took place during Covid 19 disrupted period.
